                        All methods to delete loop in floyd cycle

Here is a complete, detailed list of all common methods to REMOVE (delete) a loop in a linked list using/after Floyd’s Cycle Detection algorithm.

I’ll explain every practical approach with C++ code.

1. Standard Method (Find loop start using Floyd + Break the loop)

This is the most used and efficient method.

Steps:

Detect cycle using Floyd’s algorithm.

Find the starting node of the loop.

Traverse the loop to find the last node of the cycle.

Set its next to NULL.

Code:
void removeLoop(Node* head) {
    if (!head || !head->next) return;

    Node *slow = head, *fast = head;

    // Step 1: Detect cycle
    while (fast && fast->next) {
        slow = slow->next;
        fast = fast->next->next;

        if (slow == fast)
            break;
    }

    // No loop
    if (!fast || !fast->next) return;

    // Step 2: Find starting node of loop
    slow = head;
    while (slow != fast) {
        slow = slow->next;
        fast = fast->next;
    }

    // slow == fast → start of loop
    Node* loopStart = slow;

    // Step 3: Find node just before loopStart
    Node* temp = loopStart;
    while (temp->next != loopStart) {
        temp = temp->next;
    }

    // Step 4: Break loop
    temp->next = NULL;
}


✅ Time Complexity: O(n)
✅ Space Complexity: O(1)

2. Method Without Explicitly Finding the Start Node

You can break the loop directly after detection.

Logic:

After meeting point:

Keep fast at meeting point.

Move slow = head.

Move both one step at a time.

Instead of stopping at meeting, track the previous node of fast.

Code:
void removeLoop(Node* head) {
    Node *slow = head, *fast = head;

    while (fast && fast->next) {
        slow = slow->next;
        fast = fast->next->next;
        if (slow == fast) break;
    }

    if (!fast || !fast->next) return;

    slow = head;
    Node* prev = NULL;

    while (slow != fast) {
        prev = fast;
        slow = slow->next;
        fast = fast->next;
    }

    // Break the loop
    prev->next = NULL;
}


This avoids the separate traversal to find the last node.

3. Hashing Method (Not Floyd, but commonly asked in interviews)

This method does not use Floyd, but it is a standard alternative.

Logic:

Use unordered_set to store visited nodes.

Code:
#include <unordered_set>

void removeLoop(Node* head) {
    unordered_set<Node*> visited;
    Node* prev = NULL;
    Node* curr = head;

    while (curr != NULL) {
        if (visited.find(curr) != visited.end()) {
            prev->next = NULL;
            return;
        }
        visited.insert(curr);
        prev = curr;
        curr = curr->next;
    }
}


⛔ Uses extra space.

4. Trick Method Using Node Count of Loop

This method uses the length of the loop.

Steps:

Detect cycle.

Count loop length k.

Move one pointer k steps ahead.

Move both pointers until they meet at loop start.

Break loop.

Code:
int countLoopLength(Node* meet) {
    int count = 1;
    Node* temp = meet;
    while (temp->next != meet) {
        count++;
        temp = temp->next;
    }
    return count;
}

void removeLoop(Node* head) {
    Node *slow = head, *fast = head;

    // Detect cycle
    while (fast && fast->next) {
        slow = slow->next;
        fast = fast->next->next;
        if (slow == fast) break;
    }

    if (!fast || !fast->next) return;

    // Step 2: Count loop length
    int k = countLoopLength(slow);

    // Step 3: Move one pointer k steps
    Node* ptr1 = head;
    Node* ptr2 = head;
    for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
        ptr2 = ptr2->next;
    }

    // Step 4: Find start node
    while (ptr1 != ptr2) {
        ptr1 = ptr1->next;
        ptr2 = ptr2->next;
    }

    // Step 5: Find last node
    while (ptr2->next != ptr1) {
        ptr2 = ptr2->next;
    }

    // Break loop
    ptr2->next = NULL;
}

5. Edge Case Special Method (Self-loop)

If a node points to itself:

10 → ⬆
     ⬅

Code:
void removeLoop(Node* head) {
    if (head && head->next == head) {
        head->next = NULL;
    }
}

6. Summary of All Methods
Method	Uses Floyd?	Extra Space	Best Use Case
Find start + break	✅ Yes	❌ No	Most common
Track previous node	✅ Yes	❌ No	Cleaner version
Hashing method	❌ No	✅ Yes	Simple logic
Loop length method	✅ Yes	❌ No	When length info needed